Title: Meta.DataModel
Description: Clinical Summary

Title: Meta.EventType
Description: PatientQuery

Title: Meta.EventDateTime
Description: Displays the UTC date and time that an outgoing request is delivered or an incoming request is received.

Title: Meta.Test
Description: Indicates whether the request is a test or not.

Title: Meta.Source
Description: Contains the information for the system initiating the message, including the source ID and name.

Title: Meta.Source.ID
Description: Identifies the system initiating the message. If you have multiple OAuth API keys per environment type, this value is required. If you have only one OAuth API key per environment type, or you're using legacy API keys, this value is optional.

Title: Meta.Source.Name
Description: Displays the name of the system initiating the message.

Title: Meta.Destinations[]
Notes: Required when sending data to Redox.
Description: Contains the information for the endpoint(s) receiving the request. A request must contain at least one destination, but asynchronous requests can have more than one destination. Synchronous requests like queries can only support one destination.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].ID
Description: Identifies the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].Name
Description: Displays the name of the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Logs[]
Description: Contains the log identifier(s) for the request.

Title: Meta.Logs[].ID
Description: Identifies the request log(s) that correspond to this request. You can use this value to locate the relevant log in the Redox dashboard for support and reference.

Title: Meta.Logs[].AttemptID
Description: Identifies the request log attempt value, which is useful when retries are possible.

Title: Meta.FacilityCode
Notes: Only use this field if a health system indicates you should. The code is specific to the health system's EHR and might not be unique across health systems. In general, the facility fields within the data models (e.g. OrderingFacility) are more reliable and informative.
Description: Code for the facility related to the message.

Title: Patient.Identifiers[]
Description: List of IDs and IDTypes for the patient

Title: Patient.Identifiers[].ID
Description: ID of the Patient

Title: Patient.Identifiers[].IDType
Description: ID Type for the corresponding ID of this patient (ie. MRN, EHRID)

Title: Location.Department
Notes: This field is required for some EHRs.
Description: ID corresponding to the department from which to retrieved the patient chart.

Title: Header.Document.ID
Description: Your application's ID for the document

Title: Header.Document.SetID
Description: An ID for the document that is common across all document revisions.

Title: Header.Document.VersionNumber
Notes: When `SetID` is provided, `VersionNumber` is required.     Used when superseding or modifying a prior version of the same document.     For example, this document might be `VersionNumber` 2, and it has a     `RelatesTo[].VersionNumber` 1, the prior version with the same `RelatesTo[].SetID`.
Description: An integer version number for this revision of the document.

Title: Header.Document.RelatesTo[]
Description: The identifiers for other documents related to this document, such as prior versions that this document replaces.

Title: Header.Document.RelatesTo[].Code
Notes: FHIR [Document Relationship Type](http://hl7.org/fhir/document-relationship-type)    or CDA RelatedDocument TypeCode: `APND` (appends), `RPLC` (replaces), or `XFRM` (transforms).
Description: A code for how the related document interacts with this document.

Description: The ID of the related document

Title: Procedures
Description:
A general grouper for all things that CDA considers procedures, grouped into three kinds. 

-Observations - procedures which result in new information about a patient. 

-Procedures - procedures whose immediate and primary outcome is the alteration of the physical condition of the patient. 

-Services (Sometimes called Acts) - procedures which cannot be classified as an observation or a procedure, such as a dressing change, feeding, or teaching.

Description: Displays the name of the system initiating the message.

Description: Displays the name of the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Procedures
Description:
A general grouper for all things that CDA considers procedures, grouped into three kinds. 

-Observations - procedures which result in new information about a patient. 

-Procedures - procedures whose immediate and primary outcome is the alteration of the physical condition of the patient. 

-Services (Sometimes called Acts) - procedures which cannot be classified as an observation or a procedure, such as a dressing change, feeding, or teaching.

Title: Meta.DataModel
Description: Clinical Summary

Title: Meta.EventType
Description: VisitQuery

Title: Meta.EventDateTime
Description: Displays the UTC date and time that an outgoing request is delivered or an incoming request is received.

Title: Meta.Test
Description: Indicates whether the request is a test or not.

Title: Meta.Source
Description: Contains the information for the system initiating the message, including the source ID and name.

Title: Meta.Source.ID
Description: Identifies the system initiating the message. If you have multiple OAuth API keys per environment type, this value is required. If you have only one OAuth API key per environment type, or you're using legacy API keys, this value is optional.

Title: Meta.Source.Name
Description: Displays the name of the system initiating the message.

Title: Meta.Destinations[]
Notes: Required when sending data to Redox.
Description: Contains the information for the endpoint(s) receiving the request. A request must contain at least one destination, but asynchronous requests can have more than one destination. Synchronous requests like queries can only support one destination.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].ID
Description: Identifies the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].Name
Description: Displays the name of the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Logs[]
Description: Contains the log identifier(s) for the request.

Title: Meta.Logs[].ID
Description: Identifies the request log(s) that correspond to this request. You can use this value to locate the relevant log in the Redox dashboard for support and reference.

Title: Meta.Logs[].AttemptID
Description: Identifies the request log attempt value, which is useful when retries are possible.

Title: Meta.FacilityCode
Notes: Only use this field if a health system indicates you should. The code is specific to the health system's EHR and might not be unique across health systems. In general, the facility fields within the data models (e.g. OrderingFacility) are more reliable and informative.
Description: Code for the facility related to the message.

Description: List of IDs and IDTypes for the patient

Description: ID of the Patient

Title: Patient.Identifiers[].IDType
Description: ID Type for the corresponding ID of this patient (ie. MRN, EHRID)

Description: ID for the patient visit/encounter. Either this or a timeframe is required to accurately locate a visit.

Title: Visit.StartDateTime
Description: Beginning of the timeframe for which to request visit summaries. Either this or a visit number is required to accurately locate a visit.

Title: Visit.EndDateTime
Description: End of the timeframe for which to request visit summaries.

Title: Procedures
Description:
A general grouper for all things that CDA considers procedures, grouped into three kinds. 

-Observations - procedures which result in new information about a patient. 

-Procedures - procedures whose immediate and primary outcome is the alteration of the physical condition of the patient. 

-Services (Sometimes called Acts) - procedures which cannot be classified as an observation or a procedure, such as a dressing change, feeding, or teaching.

Title: Procedures.Observations[]
Description: These are procedures that are more observational in nature, such as an EEG or EKG.

Title: Procedures.Observations[].Code
Description: A code describing the procedure that was performed.

Title: Procedures.Observations[].CodeSystem
Notes: Either CodeSystem or CodeSystemName (preferred) is required when a Code is present.
Description: ID of the coding system to which the code belongs in OID format.

Title: Procedures
Description:
A general grouper for all things that CDA considers procedures, grouped into three kinds. 

-Observations - procedures which result in new information about a patient. 

-Procedures - procedures whose immediate and primary outcome is the alteration of the physical condition of the patient. 

-Services (Sometimes called Acts) - procedures which cannot be classified as an observation or a procedure, such as a dressing change, feeding, or teaching.

Description: This flag indicates whether a CDS alert is shown to the provider while they're placing an order in the EHR system. If the CDS alert shouldn't be visible in the EHR system, set this value to `false`. But keep in mind that if this is `false`, the provider won't see an alert while placing an order.

You can use this identifier to reconcile transactions (e.g., for billing review).       Note that multiple entries might have the same transaction identifier if a vendor supports batch enrichment.

Title: Transaction.Task
Description: Vendor-specific details about the task created to fulfill your enrichment transaction.

Title: Transaction.Task.ID
Notes: Note that this value may be the same as the Transaction.ID, depending on the vendor.
Description: You can use this identifier to check the status or results of the enrichment task later.

Title: Transaction.Task.Status
Notes: Values can be one of the following: Pending, Success
Description: The status of the enrichment task your query created.         If the status value is Success, the results of the enrichment are populated in the Entries fields.

Title: Transaction.Task.Message
Description: Describes the current status of the enrichment task your query created.

Title: Entries[]
Description: A list of data entries extracted from the natural-language content submitted in your query.

Title: Entries[].Text
Description: Contains details about the text you submitted for enrichment.

Title: Entries[].Text.Contents
Description: The text snippet from your submitted content that resulted in this specific data extract.

Title: Entries[].Text.Position
Description: Details about where in your submitted content this text snippet was located.

Title: Entries[].Text.Position.BeginOffset
Notes: For example: if the three-letter word "hat" was extracted from your text starting at character 10, it would have a BeginOffset of 10.
Description: The first character position of this snippet, which is measured from the start of your submitted content.

Title: Entries[].Text.Position.EndOffset
Notes: For example: if the three-letter word "hat" was extracted from your text starting at character 10, it would have a BeginOffset of 10 and an EndOffset of 13, because the "t" in "hat" is at character 12.
Description: The character position of the next character immediately after the end of this snippet, which is measured from the start of your submitted content.

Title: Entries[].Category
Description: A list of all categories of data that were extracted from the text contents for the entry.

Title: Entries[].Category.Name
Description: The name of the category of data extracted from the text.

Title: Entries[].Category.CertaintyScore
Description: The confidence score that the matched category is accurate: 0 is low confidence, and 1 is high confidence.

Title: Entries[].Concept.Code
Description: Code for the concept matched by the enrichment vendor.

Title: Entries[].Concept.Codeset
Description: Code set used to identify the concept matched by the enrichment vendor.

Title: Entries[].Concept.Description
Description: Description of the concept matched by the enrichment vendor.

Title: Entries[].Concept.CertaintyScore
Description: The confidence score that the matched concept is accurate: 0 is low confidence, and 1 is high confidence.

Title: Meta.DataModel
Description: Enrichment

Description: NormalizationQuery

Title: Meta.EventDateTime
Description: Displays the UTC date and time that an outgoing request is delivered or an incoming request is received.

Title: Meta.Test
Description: Indicates whether the request is a test or not.

Title: Meta.Source
Description: Contains the information for the system initiating the message, including the source ID and name.

Title: Meta.Source.ID
Description: Identifies the system initiating the message. If you have multiple OAuth API keys per environment type, this value is required. If you have only one OAuth API key per environment type, or you're using legacy API keys, this value is optional.

Title: Meta.Source.Name
Description: Displays the name of the system initiating the message.

Title: Meta.Destinations[]
Notes: Required when sending data to Redox.
Description: Contains the information for the endpoint(s) receiving the request. A request must contain at least one destination, but asynchronous requests can have more than one destination. Synchronous requests like queries can only support one destination.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].ID
Description: Identifies the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].Name
Description: Displays the name of the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Logs[]
Description: Contains the log identifier(s) for the request.

Title: Meta.Logs[].ID
Description: Identifies the request log(s) that correspond to this request. You can use this value to locate the relevant log in the Redox dashboard for support and reference.

Title: Meta.Logs[].AttemptID
Description: Identifies the request log attempt value, which is useful when retries are possible.

Title: Meta.FacilityCode
Notes: Only use this field if a health system indicates you should. The code is specific to the health system's EHR and might not be unique across health systems. In general, the facility fields within the data models (e.g. OrderingFacility) are more reliable and informative.
Description: Code for the facility related to the message.

Title: Entries[]
Description: A list of entries to be normalized. The maximum number of entries that can be included is 100.

Title: Entries[].Category
Description: The category of values in which to find this normalization entry.

Title: Entries[].EntryID
Description: The identifier of the specific entry to be normalized.         If not provided, Redox generates an identifier to populate this field in the NormalizationQueryResponse         so that you can match the normalized entry to the submitted entry.

Title: Entries[].Code
Notes: You must include either code value or description, or you can provide both.
Description: Code for the value to be normalized by the third-party vendor.

Title: Entries[].Codeset
Notes: For example: ICD-10-CM, ICD-9-CM, SNOMED CT.
Description: Code set used to identify the value to be normalized by the third-party vendor.

Title: Entries[].Description
Notes: You must include either code value or description, or you can provide both.
Description: Description of the value to be normalized by the third-party vendor.

Title: Entries[]
Description: A list of normalized entries that were submitted with the NormalizationQuery.

Title: Entries[].Category
Description: The category of values for this normalization entry.

Title: Entries[].Status
Notes: One of the following: Success, Error
Description: The outcome of this specific entry's normalization.

Title: Entries[].Transaction
Description: Contains details about the vendor that performed the enrichment.

Title: Entries[].Transaction.VendorID
Description: The identifier of the third-party vendor that processed the enrichment request.

Title: Entries[].Transaction.ID
Description: The identifier of the specific enrichment transaction, which is generated by the third-party vendor.       You can use this identifier to reconcile transactions (e.g., for billing review).       Note that multiple entries might have the same transaction identifier if a vendor supports batch enrichment.

Title: Entries[].Submitted
Description: A copy of the entry input data provided in your Normalization Query.

Title: Entries[].Submitted.Category
Notes: Categories currently supported: Problem. This is an unmodified copy of the value submitted in your Normalization Query.
Description: The category of values in which to find this normalization entry.

Title: Entries[].Submitted.EntryID
Notes: This is an unmodified copy of the value submitted in your Normalization Query.
Description: This is an unmodified copy of the value submitted in the NormalizationQuery. If you didn't provide an ID, Redox generates one for you.

Title: Entries[].Submitted.Code
Notes: You must include either code value or description, or you can provide both.  This is an unmodified copy of the value submitted in your Normalization Query.
Description: Code for the value to be normalized by the third-party vendor.

Title: Entries[].Submitted.Codeset
Notes: For example: ICD-10-CM, ICD-9-CM, SNOMED CT.  This is an unmodified copy of the value submitted in your Normalization Query.
Description: Code set used to identify the value to be normalized by the third-party vendor.

Title: Entries[].Submitted.Description
Notes: You must include either code value or description, or you can provide both.  This is an unmodified copy of the value submitted in your Normalization Query.
Description: Description of the value to be normalized by the third-party vendor.

Title: Entries[].Normalization[]
Description: The output of the normalization transaction.       If normalization results in an error, this array contains the error information.       If normalization results in a success, this array contains the normalized entry data.

Title: Entries[].Normalization[].LexicalReference
Description: The principal code value that was matched with the input data provided for this entry.

Title: Entries[].Normalization[].LexicalReference.Code
Description: The value of the normalized match for the submitted code value.

Title: Entries[].Normalization[].LexicalReference.Name
Description: The name of the normalized match of the submitted code value.

Title: Entries[].Normalization[].LexicalReference.DefaultCode
Description: The value of the default variant of the normalized match for the submitted code value.

Title: Entries[].Normalization[].LexicalReference.DefaultName
Description: The name or of the default variant of the normalized match for the submitted code value.

Title: Entries[].Normalization[].Score
Description: The quantified confidence that the Lexical Reference value matches the input data provided for this entry.

Title: Entries[].Normalization[].Score.Value
Description: The quality/certainty score for the Lexical Reference match, between `0` and `1`: an exact match has a score value of `1`.

Title: Entries[].Normalization[].Score.Description
Description: The description of the confidence score for the normalization. A score of 1 will have a description of Exact.

Title: Entries[].Normalization[].Matches[]
Description: Any related coded values associated with the matched Lexical Reference value, collected by code system.

Title: Entries[].Normalization[].Matches[].Codeset
Description: Coding system to which the related codes belong (e.g. ICD-10-CM, ICD-9-CM, SNOMED CT)

Title: Entries[].Normalization[].Matches[].Status
Notes: One of the following: Success, Not Codeable, Insufficient Data
Description: The outcome of matching the lexical reference code to this specific Code Set.

Title: Entries[].Normalization[].Matches[].Codes[]
Description: The collection of related coded values within this Match's code set, if matching was successful.

Title: Entries[].Normalization[].Matches[].Codes[].Code
Description: The code value in the indicated code set in the normalization category.

Title: Entries[].Normalization[].Matches[].Codes[].MatchPriority
Description: Indicates the priority for this match (e.g. Preferred Primary or Preferred).

Title: Entries[].Normalization[].Matches[].Codes[].Variants[]
Description: A collection of variants for the code value; for example, multiple titles might apply to the same code.

Title: Entries[].Normalization[].Matches[].Codes[].Variants[].Title
Description: A specific title of the code value variant.

Title: Entries[].Normalization[].Matches[].Codes[].Variants[].TitleStatus
Description: The status of this title for the code value variant, if a status is applicable.

Title: Entries[].Normalization[].Matches[].Codes[].Variants[].TitleType
Description: If the title of this variant can be categorized, this is the type description.

Title: Entries[].Normalization[].Matches[].Codes[].Variants[].ExtendedProperties[]
Description: The collection of any metadata properties about this specific code variant.

Title: Entries[].Normalization[].Matches[].Codes[].Variants[].ExtendedProperties[].Category
Description: The category name of this set of extended properties of this variant.

Title: Entries[].Normalization[].Matches[].Codes[].Variants[].ExtendedProperties[].Properties[]
Description: The collection of extended properties within the given category.

Title: Entries[].Normalization[].Matches[].Codes[].Variants[].ExtendedProperties[].Properties[].Property
Description: The extended property name or code within the given category.

Title: Entries[].Normalization[].Matches[].Codes[].Variants[].ExtendedProperties[].Properties[].Value
Description: The value of the extended property within the given category.

Title: Entries[].Error
Description: If enrichment operation results in an error, this object contains the error details.       If the operation results in a success, this object is null. Note that it's possible for some operations in a request to succeed while others fail.

Title: Entries[].Error.Code
Description: Contains the error code as defined by the third-party vendor.

Title: Entries[].Error.Message
Description: Describes the error that disrupted the enrichment operation.

Description: Displays the UTC date and time that an outgoing request is delivered or an incoming request is received.

Description: Indicates whether the request is a test or not.

Title: Meta.Source
Description: Contains the information for the system initiating the message, including the source ID and name.

Title: Meta.Source.ID
Description: Identifies the system initiating the message. If you have multiple OAuth API keys per environment type, this value is required. If you have only one OAuth API key per environment type, or you're using legacy API keys, this value is optional.

Title: Meta.Source.Name
Description: Displays the name of the system initiating the message.

Title: Meta.Destinations[]
Notes: Required when sending data to Redox.
Description: Contains the information for the endpoint(s) receiving the request. A request must contain at least one destination, but asynchronous requests can have more than one destination. Synchronous requests like queries can only support one destination.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].ID
Description: Identifies the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].Name
Description: Displays the name of the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Logs[]
Description: Contains the log identifier(s) for the request.

Title: Meta.Logs[].ID
Description: Identifies the request log(s) that correspond to this request. You can use this value to locate the relevant log in the Redox dashboard for support and reference.

Title: Meta.Logs[].AttemptID
Description: Identifies the request log attempt value, which is useful when retries are possible.

Title: Meta.FacilityCode
Notes: Only use this field if a health system indicates you should. The code is specific to the health system's EHR and might not be unique across health systems. In general, the facility fields within the data models (e.g. OrderingFacility) are more reliable and informative.
Description: Code for the facility related to the message.

Description: Contains the information for the system initiating the message, including the source ID and name.

Title: Meta.Source.ID
Description: Identifies the system initiating the message. If you have multiple OAuth API keys per environment type, this value is required. If you have only one OAuth API key per environment type, or you're using legacy API keys, this value is optional.

Title: Meta.Source.Name
Description: Displays the name of the system initiating the message.

Title: Meta.Destinations[]
Notes: Required when sending data to Redox.
Description: Contains the information for the endpoint(s) receiving the request. A request must contain at least one destination, but asynchronous requests can have more than one destination. Synchronous requests like queries can only support one destination.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].ID
Description: Identifies the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Description: Displays the name of the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Description: Contains the log identifier(s) for the request.

Description: Identifies the request log(s) that correspond to this request. You can use this value to locate the relevant log in the Redox dashboard for support and reference.

Title: Meta.Logs[].AttemptID
Description: Identifies the request log attempt value, which is useful when retries are possible.

Notes: Only use this field if a health system indicates you should. The code is specific to the health system's EHR and might not be unique across health systems. In general, the facility fields within the data models (e.g. OrderingFacility) are more reliable and informative.
Description: Code for the facility related to the message.

Title: Observations[]
Description: List of values to be added to the flowsheet

Title: Observations[].DateTime
Description: DateTime the value was recorded

Title: Observations[].Value
Notes: For example, if the value is a heart rate, this will be 65
Description: Value to be recorded

Title: Observations[].ValueType
Description: Data type of the value

Title: Observations[].Units
Notes: If the Code is "Heart Rate", this may be "BPM"
Description: Units of the value

Title: Observations[].Code
Notes: This is usually provided by the EMR or you will asked to provide a list of codes you can send. For example, this is where you would specify "Heart Rate" for heart rate values.
Description: Code for the flowsheet row that the value should file to

Title: Observations[].Codeset
Description: Codeset used to identify the code

Title: Observations[].Description
Description: Description of the flowsheet row

Title: Observations[].Status
Description: Status of the observation

Title: Observations[].Notes[]
Description: Notes about the observation

Title: Observations[].Observer.ID
Notes: Typically represents an actual person, but may also be linked to device in some EHRs
Description: Optional code indicating who made the observation

Title: Observations[].Observer.IDType
Description: ID type of the ID for the Observer

Title: Observations[].Observer.FirstName
Description: Optional code indicating who made the observation

Title: Observations[].Observer.LastName
Description: Optional code indicating who made the observation

Title: Observations[].ReferenceRange
Notes: Numeric observation values will use the low and high properties. Non-numeric observation values will put the normal value in the text property.
Description: Reference range for the observation

Title: Observations[].ReferenceRange.Low
Description: Lower bound for a normal observation

Title: Observations[].ReferenceRange.High
Description: Upper bound for a normal observation

Title: Observations[].ReferenceRange.Text
Description: The normal value for non-numeric observations

Title: Observations[].AbnormalFlag
Notes: One of the following: "Normal", "Low", "Very Low", "High", "Very High", "Abnormal", "Very Abnormal". Abnormal flags starting with "Very" indicate a panic level. The "High" and "Low" flags should be used with Numeric result values while "Abnormal" should be used with non-numeric values.
Description: Indication of whether the observation was abnormal

Description: Update

Title: Meta.EventDateTime
Description: Displays the UTC date and time that an outgoing request is delivered or an incoming request is received.

Title: Meta.Test
Description: Indicates whether the request is a test or not.

Title: Meta.Source
Description: Contains the information for the system initiating the message, including the source ID and name.

Title: Meta.Source.ID
Description: Identifies the system initiating the message. If you have multiple OAuth API keys per environment type, this value is required. If you have only one OAuth API key per environment type, or you're using legacy API keys, this value is optional.

Title: Meta.Source.Name
Description: Displays the name of the system initiating the message.

Title: Meta.Destinations[]
Notes: Required when sending data to Redox.
Description: Contains the information for the endpoint(s) receiving the request. A request must contain at least one destination, but asynchronous requests can have more than one destination. Synchronous requests like queries can only support one destination.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].ID
Description: Identifies the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].Name
Description: Displays the name of the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Logs[]
Description: Contains the log identifier(s) for the request.

Title: Meta.Logs[].ID
Description: Identifies the request log(s) that correspond to this request. You can use this value to locate the relevant log in the Redox dashboard for support and reference.

Title: Meta.Logs[].AttemptID
Description: Identifies the request log attempt value, which is useful when retries are possible.

Title: Meta.FacilityCode
Notes: Only use this field if a health system indicates you should. The code is specific to the health system's EHR and might not be unique across health systems. In general, the facility fields within the data models (e.g. OrderingFacility) are more reliable and informative.
Description: Code for the facility related to the message.

Description: Displays the UTC date and time that an outgoing request is delivered or an incoming request is received.

Description: Indicates whether the request is a test or not.

Title: Meta.Source
Description: Contains the information for the system initiating the message, including the source ID and name.

Title: Meta.Source.ID
Description: Identifies the system initiating the message. If you have multiple OAuth API keys per environment type, this value is required. If you have only one OAuth API key per environment type, or you're using legacy API keys, this value is optional.

Title: Meta.Source.Name
Description: Displays the name of the system initiating the message.

Title: Meta.Destinations[]
Notes: Required when sending data to Redox.
Description: Contains the information for the endpoint(s) receiving the request. A request must contain at least one destination, but asynchronous requests can have more than one destination. Synchronous requests like queries can only support one destination.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].ID
Description: Identifies the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].Name
Description: Displays the name of the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Logs[]
Description: Contains the log identifier(s) for the request.

Title: Meta.Logs[].ID
Description: Identifies the request log(s) that correspond to this request. You can use this value to locate the relevant log in the Redox dashboard for support and reference.

Title: Meta.Logs[].AttemptID
Description: Identifies the request log attempt value, which is useful when retries are possible.

Title: Meta.FacilityCode
Notes: Only use this field if a health system indicates you should. The code is specific to the health system's EHR and might not be unique across health systems. In general, the facility fields within the data models (e.g. OrderingFacility) are more reliable and informative.
Description: Code for the facility related to the message.

Description: Displays the UTC date and time that an outgoing request is delivered or an incoming request is received.

Title: Meta.Test
Description: Indicates whether the request is a test or not.

Title: Meta.Source
Description: Contains the information for the system initiating the message, including the source ID and name.

Title: Meta.Source.ID
Description: Identifies the system initiating the message. If you have multiple OAuth API keys per environment type, this value is required. If you have only one OAuth API key per environment type, or you're using legacy API keys, this value is optional.

Title: Meta.Source.Name
Description: Displays the name of the system initiating the message.

Title: Meta.Destinations[]
Notes: Required when sending data to Redox.
Description: Contains the information for the endpoint(s) receiving the request. A request must contain at least one destination, but asynchronous requests can have more than one destination. Synchronous requests like queries can only support one destination.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].ID
Description: Identifies the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].Name
Description: Displays the name of the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Logs[]
Description: Contains the log identifier(s) for the request.

Title: Meta.Logs[].ID
Description: Identifies the request log(s) that correspond to this request. You can use this value to locate the relevant log in the Redox dashboard for support and reference.

Title: Meta.Logs[].AttemptID
Description: Identifies the request log attempt value, which is useful when retries are possible.

Title: Meta.FacilityCode
Notes: Only use this field if a health system indicates you should. The code is specific to the health system's EHR and might not be unique across health systems. In general, the facility fields within the data models (e.g. OrderingFacility) are more reliable and informative.
Description: Code for the facility related to the message.

Title: Meta.Source
Description: Contains the information for the system initiating the message, including the source ID and name.

Title: Meta.Source.ID
Description: Identifies the system initiating the message. If you have multiple OAuth API keys per environment type, this value is required. If you have only one OAuth API key per environment type, or you're using legacy API keys, this value is optional.

Title: Meta.Source.Name
Description: Displays the name of the system initiating the message.

Title: Meta.Destinations[]
Notes: Required when sending data to Redox.
Description: Contains the information for the endpoint(s) receiving the request. A request must contain at least one destination, but asynchronous requests can have more than one destination. Synchronous requests like queries can only support one destination.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].ID
Description: Identifies the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Description: Displays the name of the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Description: Contains the log identifier(s) for the request.

Title: Meta.Logs[].ID
Description: Identifies the request log(s) that correspond to this request. You can use this value to locate the relevant log in the Redox dashboard for support and reference.

Title: Meta.Logs[].AttemptID
Description: Identifies the request log attempt value, which is useful when retries are possible.

Title: Meta.FacilityCode
Notes: Only use this field if a health system indicates you should. The code is specific to the health system's EHR and might not be unique across health systems. In general, the facility fields within the data models (e.g. OrderingFacility) are more reliable and informative.
Description: Code for the facility related to the message.

Title: Meta.EventType
Description: Query

Title: Meta.EventDateTime
Description: Displays the UTC date and time that an outgoing request is delivered or an incoming request is received.

Title: Meta.Test
Description: Indicates whether the request is a test or not.

Title: Meta.Source
Description: Contains the information for the system initiating the message, including the source ID and name.

Title: Meta.Source.ID
Description: Identifies the system initiating the message. If you have multiple OAuth API keys per environment type, this value is required. If you have only one OAuth API key per environment type, or you're using legacy API keys, this value is optional.

Title: Meta.Source.Name
Description: Displays the name of the system initiating the message.

Title: Meta.Destinations[]
Notes: Required when sending data to Redox.
Description: Contains the information for the endpoint(s) receiving the request. A request must contain at least one destination, but asynchronous requests can have more than one destination. Synchronous requests like queries can only support one destination.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].ID
Description: Identifies the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].Name
Description: Displays the name of the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Logs[]
Description: Contains the log identifier(s) for the request.

Title: Meta.Logs[].ID
Description: Identifies the request log(s) that correspond to this request. You can use this value to locate the relevant log in the Redox dashboard for support and reference.

Title: Meta.Logs[].AttemptID
Description: Identifies the request log attempt value, which is useful when retries are possible.

Title: Meta.FacilityCode
Notes: Only use this field if a health system indicates you should. The code is specific to the health system's EHR and might not be unique across health systems. In general, the facility fields within the data models (e.g. OrderingFacility) are more reliable and informative.
Description: Code for the facility related to the message.

Description: Array of patient visits to query on.

Notes: The type of note to retrieve (E.g. Consent Form, Treatment Plan)
Description: Array of document types to query on.

Title: DocumentIDs[]
Description: Array of a document identifier to query.

Description: Identifies the request log attempt value, which is useful when retries are possible.

Description: Displays the UTC date and time that an outgoing request is delivered or an incoming request is received.

Description: Indicates whether the request is a test or not.

Title: Meta.Source
Description: Contains the information for the system initiating the message, including the source ID and name.

Title: Meta.Source.ID
Description: Identifies the system initiating the message. If you have multiple OAuth API keys per environment type, this value is required. If you have only one OAuth API key per environment type, or you're using legacy API keys, this value is optional.

Title: Meta.Source.Name
Description: Displays the name of the system initiating the message.

Title: Meta.Destinations[]
Notes: Required when sending data to Redox.
Description: Contains the information for the endpoint(s) receiving the request. A request must contain at least one destination, but asynchronous requests can have more than one destination. Synchronous requests like queries can only support one destination.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].ID
Description: Identifies the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].Name
Description: Displays the name of the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Logs[]
Description: Contains the log identifier(s) for the request.

Title: Meta.Logs[].ID
Description: Identifies the request log(s) that correspond to this request. You can use this value to locate the relevant log in the Redox dashboard for support and reference.

Title: Meta.Logs[].AttemptID
Description: Identifies the request log attempt value, which is useful when retries are possible.

Title: Meta.FacilityCode
Notes: Only use this field if a health system indicates you should. The code is specific to the health system's EHR and might not be unique across health systems. In general, the facility fields within the data models (e.g. OrderingFacility) are more reliable and informative.
Description: Code for the facility related to the message.

Title: EndDateTime
Description: End of the time range to search for orders. This is based on the Order.TransactionDateTime.

Title: OrderIDs[]
Notes: If multiple orders are provided, all matching orders will be returned.
Description: Array of order IDs assigned by the ordering system to filter queries by.

Notes: All orders associated with any of the procedure codes provided will be returned.

Title: Meta.DataModel
Description: PatientAdmin

Title: Meta.EventType
Description: Cancel

Title: Meta.EventDateTime
Description: Displays the UTC date and time that an outgoing request is delivered or an incoming request is received.

Title: Meta.CanceledEvent
Description: Designates the type of patient event being canceled (e.g., arrival, discharge, preadmit)

Title: Meta.Test
Description: Indicates whether the request is a test or not.

Title: Meta.Source
Description: Contains the information for the system initiating the message, including the source ID and name.

Title: Meta.Source.ID
Description: Identifies the system initiating the message. If you have multiple OAuth API keys per environment type, this value is required. If you have only one OAuth API key per environment type, or you're using legacy API keys, this value is optional.

Title: Meta.Source.Name
Description: Displays the name of the system initiating the message.

Title: Meta.Destinations[]
Notes: Required when sending data to Redox.
Description: Contains the information for the endpoint(s) receiving the request. A request must contain at least one destination, but asynchronous requests can have more than one destination. Synchronous requests like queries can only support one destination.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].ID
Description: Identifies the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].Name
Description: Displays the name of the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Logs[]
Description: Contains the log identifier(s) for the request.

Title: Meta.Logs[].ID
Description: Identifies the request log(s) that correspond to this request. You can use this value to locate the relevant log in the Redox dashboard for support and reference.

Title: Meta.Logs[].AttemptID
Description: Identifies the request log attempt value, which is useful when retries are possible.

Title: Meta.FacilityCode
Notes: Only use this field if a health system indicates you should. The code is specific to the health system's EHR and might not be unique across health systems. In general, the facility fields within the data models (e.g. OrderingFacility) are more reliable and informative.
Description: Code for the facility related to the message.

Description: Contains the information for the system initiating the message, including the source ID and name.

Title: Meta.Source.ID
Description: Identifies the system initiating the message. If you have multiple OAuth API keys per environment type, this value is required. If you have only one OAuth API key per environment type, or you're using legacy API keys, this value is optional.

Title: Meta.Source.Name
Description: Displays the name of the system initiating the message.

Title: Meta.Destinations[]
Notes: Required when sending data to Redox.
Description: Contains the information for the endpoint(s) receiving the request. A request must contain at least one destination, but asynchronous requests can have more than one destination. Synchronous requests like queries can only support one destination.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].ID
Description: Identifies the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].Name
Description: Displays the name of the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Logs[]
Description: Contains the log identifier(s) for the request.

Title: Meta.Logs[].ID
Description: Identifies the request log(s) that correspond to this request. You can use this value to locate the relevant log in the Redox dashboard for support and reference.

Title: Meta.Logs[].AttemptID
Description: Identifies the request log attempt value, which is useful when retries are possible.

Title: Meta.FacilityCode
Notes: Only use this field if a health system indicates you should. The code is specific to the health system's EHR and might not be unique across health systems. In general, the facility fields within the data models (e.g. OrderingFacility) are more reliable and informative.
Description: Code for the facility related to the message.

Description: Contains the information for the system initiating the message, including the source ID and name.

Title: Meta.Source.ID
Description: Identifies the system initiating the message. If you have multiple OAuth API keys per environment type, this value is required. If you have only one OAuth API key per environment type, or you're using legacy API keys, this value is optional.

Title: Meta.Source.Name
Description: Displays the name of the system initiating the message.

Title: Meta.Destinations[]
Notes: Required when sending data to Redox.
Description: Contains the information for the endpoint(s) receiving the request. A request must contain at least one destination, but asynchronous requests can have more than one destination. Synchronous requests like queries can only support one destination.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].ID
Description: Identifies the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].Name
Description: Displays the name of the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Logs[]
Description: Contains the log identifier(s) for the request.

Title: Meta.Logs[].ID
Description: Identifies the request log(s) that correspond to this request. You can use this value to locate the relevant log in the Redox dashboard for support and reference.

Title: Meta.Logs[].AttemptID
Description: Identifies the request log attempt value, which is useful when retries are possible.

Title: Meta.FacilityCode
Notes: Only use this field if a health system indicates you should. The code is specific to the health system's EHR and might not be unique across health systems. In general, the facility fields within the data models (e.g. OrderingFacility) are more reliable and informative.
Description: Code for the facility related to the message.

Description: Displays the name of the system initiating the message.

Title: Meta.Destinations[]
Notes: Required when sending data to Redox.
Description: Contains the information for the endpoint(s) receiving the request. A request must contain at least one destination, but asynchronous requests can have more than one destination. Synchronous requests like queries can only support one destination.

Description: Displays the name of the system initiating the message.

Title: Meta.Destinations[]
Notes: Required when sending data to Redox.
Description: Contains the information for the endpoint(s) receiving the request. A request must contain at least one destination, but asynchronous requests can have more than one destination. Synchronous requests like queries can only support one destination.

Description: Identifies the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.DataModel
Description: PatientAdmin

Title: Meta.EventType
Description: Transfer

Title: Meta.EventDateTime
Description: Displays the UTC date and time that an outgoing request is delivered or an incoming request is received.

Title: Meta.Test
Description: Indicates whether the request is a test or not.

Title: Meta.Source
Description: Contains the information for the system initiating the message, including the source ID and name.

Title: Meta.Source.ID
Description: Identifies the system initiating the message. If you have multiple OAuth API keys per environment type, this value is required. If you have only one OAuth API key per environment type, or you're using legacy API keys, this value is optional.

Title: Meta.Source.Name
Description: Displays the name of the system initiating the message.

Title: Meta.Destinations[]
Notes: Required when sending data to Redox.
Description: Contains the information for the endpoint(s) receiving the request. A request must contain at least one destination, but asynchronous requests can have more than one destination. Synchronous requests like queries can only support one destination.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].ID
Description: Identifies the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].Name
Description: Displays the name of the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Logs[]
Description: Contains the log identifier(s) for the request.

Title: Meta.Logs[].ID
Description: Identifies the request log(s) that correspond to this request. You can use this value to locate the relevant log in the Redox dashboard for support and reference.

Title: Meta.Logs[].AttemptID
Description: Identifies the request log attempt value, which is useful when retries are possible.

Title: Meta.FacilityCode
Notes: Only use this field if a health system indicates you should. The code is specific to the health system's EHR and might not be unique across health systems. In general, the facility fields within the data models (e.g. OrderingFacility) are more reliable and informative.
Description: Code for the facility related to the message.

Description: Displays a unique identifier for the patient visit.

Description: Contains the information for the system initiating the message, including the source ID and name.

Description: Identifies the system initiating the message. If you have multiple OAuth API keys per environment type, this value is required. If you have only one OAuth API key per environment type, or you're using legacy API keys, this value is optional.

Description: Displays the name of the system initiating the message.

Notes: Required when sending data to Redox.

Description: Identifies the request log(s) that correspond to this request. You can use this value to locate the relevant log in the Redox dashboard for support and reference.

Title: Meta.Logs[].AttemptID
Description: Identifies the request log attempt value, which is useful when retries are possible.

Description: Identifies the system initiating the message. If you have multiple OAuth API keys per environment type, this value is required. If you have only one OAuth API key per environment type, or you're using legacy API keys, this value is optional.

Title: Meta.Source.Name
Description: Displays the name of the system initiating the message.

Title: Meta.Destinations[]
Notes: Required when sending data to Redox.
Description: Contains the information for the endpoint(s) receiving the request. A request must contain at least one destination, but asynchronous requests can have more than one destination. Synchronous requests like queries can only support one destination.

Title: Meta.Logs[].AttemptID
Description: Identifies the request log attempt value, which is useful when retries are possible.

Notes: Only use this field if a health system indicates you should. The code is specific to the health system's EHR and might not be unique across health systems. In general, the facility fields within the data models (e.g. OrderingFacility) are more reliable and informative.
Description: Code for the facility related to the message.

Notes: If both facility and department are specified, the results will only include patient visits that match both the facility and the department.
Description: Specify one or more facilities to filter the census results. If multiple facilities are included, the results will contain all patient visits in any of the specified facilities.

Description: Code for the assignment

Description: Code set used to identify the assignment

Description: Topic of the education assignment

Description: Code for the assignment topic

Description: Description of the assignment topic

Title: Education[].Assignments[].InstanceID
Description: Unique ID that is assigned to the instance of the education resource

Title: Education[].Assignments[].CreatedDateTime
Description: The date and time the instance of the education assignment was created

Title: Education[].Assignments[].Status
Notes: Values will be one of the following: Active, Resolved, Deleted

Title: Education[].Assignments[].ActionStatus
Notes: Values will be one of the following: Assign, Delete, Update
Description: The action taken on the instance of education assignment

Description: The date and time the action was taken on the instance of education assignment

Description: The learner type assigned

Description: The type of content assigned to the learner

Description: An indication of how eager the learner is to engage in the education

Title: Education[].Assignments[].Assignees[].Response
Notes: Example: Verbalized understanding, Cannot demonstrate understanding
Description: The response of the learner once the education is complete

Title: Education[].Assignments[].Assignees[].Notes[]
Description: Notes about the assignee's assignment

Description: Displays the name of the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Description: Identifies the request log(s) that correspond to this request. You can use this value to locate the relevant log in the Redox dashboard for support and reference.

Description: Identifies the request log attempt value, which is useful when retries are possible.

Description: Code for the facility related to the message.

Description: AuthResponse

Title: Meta.EventDateTime
Description: Displays the UTC date and time that an outgoing request is delivered or an incoming request is received.

Title: Meta.Test
Description: Indicates whether the request is a test or not.

Title: Meta.Source
Description: Contains the information for the system initiating the message, including the source ID and name.

Title: Meta.Source.ID
Description: Identifies the system initiating the message. If you have multiple OAuth API keys per environment type, this value is required. If you have only one OAuth API key per environment type, or you're using legacy API keys, this value is optional.

Title: Meta.Source.Name
Description: Displays the name of the system initiating the message.

Title: Meta.Destinations[]
Notes: Required when sending data to Redox.
Description: Contains the information for the endpoint(s) receiving the request. A request must contain at least one destination, but asynchronous requests can have more than one destination. Synchronous requests like queries can only support one destination.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].ID
Description: Identifies the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].Name
Description: Displays the name of the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Logs[]
Description: Contains the log identifier(s) for the request.

Title: Meta.Logs[].ID
Description: Identifies the request log(s) that correspond to this request. You can use this value to locate the relevant log in the Redox dashboard for support and reference.

Title: Meta.Logs[].AttemptID
Description: Identifies the request log attempt value, which is useful when retries are possible.

Title: Meta.FacilityCode
Notes: Only use this field if a health system indicates you should. The code is specific to the health system's EHR and might not be unique across health systems. In general, the facility fields within the data models (e.g. OrderingFacility) are more reliable and informative.
Description: Code for the facility related to the message.

Title: Study.Description
Description: Full description of the study

Title: Study.Status
Notes:
Not yet recruiting: Participants are not yet being recruited
        Recruiting: Participants are currently being recruited, whether or not any participants have yet been enrolled
        Enrolling by invitation: Participants are being (or will be) selected from a predetermined population
        Active, not recruiting: Study is continuing, meaning participants are receiving an intervention or being examined, but new participants are not currently being recruited or enrolled
        Completed: The study has concluded normally; participants are no longer receiving an intervention or being examined (that is, last participants last visit has occurred)
        Suspended: Study halted prematurely but potentially will resume
        Terminated: Study halted prematurely and will not resume; participants are no longer being examined or receiving intervention
        Withdrawn: Study halted prematurely, prior to enrollment of first participant
Description: What state the study is currently in. Drawn from the clinicaltrials.gov "[Overall Recruitment Statuses](https://prsinfo.clinicaltrials.gov/definitions.html)".

Title: Study.StartDateTime
Description: The estimated date on which the clinical study will be open for recruitment of participants.

Notes: Either CodeSystem or CodeSystemName (preferred) is required when a Code is present.
Description: Coding system to which the code belongs (e.g. SNOMED CT, LOINC, RxNorm, CVX, ICD9, ICD10)

Title: Study.Design
Description: Information about how the trial will run.

Title: Study.Design.Purpose
Notes:
Treatment: One or more interventions are being evaluated for treating a disease, syndrome, or condition.
        Prevention: One or more interventions are being assessed for preventing the development of a specific disease or health condition.
        Diagnostic: One or more interventions are being evaluated for identifying a disease or health condition.
        Supportive Care: One or more interventions are evaluated for maximizing comfort, minimizing side effects, or mitigating against a decline in the participant's health or function.
        Screening: One or more interventions are assessed or examined for identifying a condition, or risk factors for a condition, in people who are not yet known to have the condition or risk factor.
        Health Services Research: One or more interventions for evaluating the delivery, processes, management, organization, or financing of healthcare.
        Basic Science: One or more interventions for examining the basic mechanism of action (for example, physiology or biomechanics of an intervention).
        Device Feasibility: An intervention of a device product is being evaluated in a small clinical trial (generally fewer than 10 participants) to determine the feasibility of the product; or a clinical trial to test a prototype device for feasibility and not health outcomes. Such studies are conducted to confirm the design and operating specifications of a device before beginning a full clinical trial.
        Other: None of the other options applies.
Description: The objective of the study.

Title: Study.Design.Phase
Notes:
N/A: Trials without phases (for example, studies of devices or behavioral interventions).
        Early Phase 1 (Formerly listed as "Phase 0"): Exploratory trials, involving very limited human exposure, with no therapeutic or diagnostic intent (e.g., screening studies, microdose studies). See FDA guidance on exploratory IND studies for more information.
        Phase 1: Includes initial studies to determine the metabolism and pharmacologic actions of drugs in humans, the side effects associated with increasing doses, and to gain early evidence of effectiveness; may include healthy participants and/or patients.
        Phase 1/Phase 2: Trials that are a combination of phases 1 and 2.
        Phase 2: Includes controlled clinical studies conducted to evaluate the effectiveness of the drug for a particular indication or indications in participants with the disease or condition under study and to determine the common short-term side effects and risks.
        Phase 2/Phase 3: Trials that are a combination of phases 2 and 3.
        Phase 3: Includes trials conducted after preliminary evidence suggesting effectiveness of the drug has been obtained, and are intended to gather additional information to evaluate the overall benefit-risk relationship of the drug.
        Phase 4: Studies of FDA-approved drugs to delineate additional information including the drug's risks, benefits, and optimal use.
Description: For studies of drug products, the numerical phase of the study.

Title: Meta.DataModel
Description: Results

Title: Meta.EventType
Description: Query

Title: Meta.EventDateTime
Description: Displays the UTC date and time that an outgoing request is delivered or an incoming request is received.

Title: Meta.Test
Description: Indicates whether the request is a test or not.

Title: Meta.Source
Description: Contains the information for the system initiating the message, including the source ID and name.

Title: Meta.Source.ID
Description: Identifies the system initiating the message. If you have multiple OAuth API keys per environment type, this value is required. If you have only one OAuth API key per environment type, or you're using legacy API keys, this value is optional.

Title: Meta.Source.Name
Description: Displays the name of the system initiating the message.

Title: Meta.Destinations[]
Notes: Required when sending data to Redox.
Description: Contains the information for the endpoint(s) receiving the request. A request must contain at least one destination, but asynchronous requests can have more than one destination. Synchronous requests like queries can only support one destination.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].ID
Description: Identifies the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].Name
Description: Displays the name of the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Logs[]
Description: Contains the log identifier(s) for the request.

Title: Meta.Logs[].ID
Description: Identifies the request log(s) that correspond to this request. You can use this value to locate the relevant log in the Redox dashboard for support and reference.

Title: Meta.Logs[].AttemptID
Description: Identifies the request log attempt value, which is useful when retries are possible.

Title: Meta.FacilityCode
Notes: Only use this field if a health system indicates you should. The code is specific to the health system's EHR and might not be unique across health systems. In general, the facility fields within the data models (e.g. OrderingFacility) are more reliable and informative.
Description: Code for the facility related to the message.

Title: Patients[]
Notes: If multiple patients are provided, all results associated with any of the patients will be returned.
Description: Array of patients to filter results on.

Title: Patients[].Identifiers[]
Notes: If multiple identifiers are provided, only patients with all identifiers will be considered.
Description: List of IDs and ID types that identify the patient

Title: Patients[].Identifiers[].ID
Description: ID for the patient

Title: Patients[].Identifiers[].IDType
Description: Type of ID

Title: Completion
Description: Time range to search for results. The query will be over the DateTime at which the individual results were composed into a report and released.

Title: Completion.StartDateTime
Description: Start of the time range to search for results.

Title: Completion.EndDateTime
Description: End of the time range to search for results.

Title: ResultStatuses[]
Notes: If multiple result status values are provided, all results with any of the statuses will be returned.
Description: Array of result statuses to filter queries by.

Title: OrderIDs[]
Notes: If multiple orders are provided, all results associated with any of the orders will be returned.
Description: Array of order IDs assigned by the ordering system to filter queries by.

Title: RelatedGroupIDs[]
Notes: If multiple related group IDs are provided, all results associated with any of the group IDs will be returned.
Description: Array of related group IDs assigned by the ordering system to filter queries by.

Title: Procedures[]
Notes: All results associated with any of the procedure codes provided will be returned.
Description: Array of procedures to query for related results.

Title: Procedures[].Code
Description: Code for the procedure

Title: Procedures[].Codeset
Notes: If no code set is specified, a health system specific identifier is being used.
Description: Code set used to identify the procedure

Title: Location.Department
Notes: This field is required for some EHRs.
Description: ID corresponding to the department from which to retrieved the patient chart.

Title: LastUpdated
Description: An alternative time range to search for results. Instead of querying over a clinically relevant timestamp like Completion, this searches over database update timestamps.

Title: LastUpdated.StartDateTime
Description: Allows for searching on updated time of results. This is the start of the time range to search in.

Title: LastUpdated.EndDateTime
Description: Allows for searching on updated time of results. This is the end of the time range to search in.

Title: Meta.DataModel
Description: Scheduling

Title: Meta.EventType
Description: Cancel

Title: Meta.EventDateTime
Description: Displays the UTC date and time that an outgoing request is delivered or an incoming request is received.

Title: Meta.Test
Description: Indicates whether the request is a test or not.

Title: Meta.Source
Description: Contains the information for the system initiating the message, including the source ID and name.

Title: Meta.Source.ID
Description: Identifies the system initiating the message. If you have multiple OAuth API keys per environment type, this value is required. If you have only one OAuth API key per environment type, or you're using legacy API keys, this value is optional.

Title: Meta.Source.Name
Description: Displays the name of the system initiating the message.

Title: Meta.Destinations[]
Notes: Required when sending data to Redox.
Description: Contains the information for the endpoint(s) receiving the request. A request must contain at least one destination, but asynchronous requests can have more than one destination. Synchronous requests like queries can only support one destination.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].ID
Description: Identifies the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].Name
Description: Displays the name of the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Logs[]
Description: Contains the log identifier(s) for the request.

Title: Meta.Logs[].ID
Description: Identifies the request log(s) that correspond to this request. You can use this value to locate the relevant log in the Redox dashboard for support and reference.

Title: Meta.Logs[].AttemptID
Description: Identifies the request log attempt value, which is useful when retries are possible.

Title: Meta.FacilityCode
Notes: Only use this field if a health system indicates you should. The code is specific to the health system's EHR and might not be unique across health systems. In general, the facility fields within the data models (e.g. OrderingFacility) are more reliable and informative.
Description: Code for the facility related to the message.

Notes: Additional information that may come from patient-completed forms or other sources
Description: Description of the information element

Description: Displays the value of the corresponding appointment info code. For example, the code identifies the question being answered, and this property contains the answer.

Title: Visit.VisitNumber
Description: Displays the unique identifier for the related patient visit.

Title: Visit.AccountNumber
Notes: Not supported with data on demand.
Description: Contains an identifier that can span several visits often related to the same patient condition (e.g., surgeries, research study, pregnancy). In other words, the account number can be used to link related visits.

Title: Visit.VisitDateTime
Description: Contains the scheduled date and time of the appointment.

Title: Visit.PatientClass
Description: Classifies the department or type of patient care. Patient class is used in many EHR systems to determine where to put the patient (e.g., inpatient, outpatient, emergency).

Title: Visit.Status
Description: Indicates the status of the visit.

Title: Visit.Duration
Description: Defines the length of the appointment in minutes.

Title: Visit.Reason
Description: Contains is a patient-friendly value that provides context for the purpose of the appointment (e.g., knee pain). This differs from the Visit Type since it can include a clinical component.

Title: Visit.CancelReason
Description: Reason the visit was canceled

Title: Visit.Type
Notes: Not supported with data on demand.
Description: Displays an administrative value used primarily for bidirectional exchange to update EHR system schedules.

Title: Visit.Instructions[]
Notes: Not supported with data on demand.
Description: Contains any relevant instructions for the patient visit.

Description: Indicates that a limit was reached, and not all data was returned. If true, the sender may want to restrict the parameters of the request in order to match fewer results.

Notes: This is used for SMART App Launch and other OAuth/OpenID Connect flows where an access token is provided in addition to the SSO claims. The SessionID can be used on subsequent Redox API requests to fetch data.
Description: Session ID to be passed through for 3rd party sessions.

Title: Meta.SessionBaseURL
Notes: See our docs on [SMART via Redox](https://fhir.redoxengine.com/getting_started/smart) for more details on how to use this field.
Description: The Base URL to use when issuing Redox FHIR queries within the SSO session context.

Notes: Required when sending data to Redox
Description: List of destinations to send your message to. All messages must have at least one destination. Queries accept only one destination.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].ID
Description: ID of the destination

Title: Meta.Destinations[].Name
Description: Name of the destination

Title: Meta.FacilityCode
Notes: Only use this field if a health system indicates you should. The code is specific to the health system's EHR and might not be unique across health systems. In general, the facility fields within the data models (e.g. OrderingFacility) are more reliable and informative.
Description: Code for the facility related to the message.

Title: Subject
Notes: The `Subject` value is a case sensitive string.
Description: Subject Identifier. A locally unique and never reassigned identifier for the End-User, which is intended to be consumed by the Client.

Title: Expiration
Notes: Typically we send date/times in ISO 8601 but this is sent as an epoch to stay compatible with JWT.
Description:
Expiration time on or after which the ID Token MUST NOT be accepted for processing. 
    The processing of this parameter requires that the current date/time MUST be before the expiration date/time listed in the value. 
    Its value is a JSON number representing the number of seconds from 1970-01-01T0:0:0Z as measured in UTC until the date/time.

Title: IssuedAt
Notes: Typically we send date/times in ISO 8601 but this is sent as an epoch to stay compatible with JWT.
Description: Time at which the JWT was issued. Its value is a JSON number representing the number of seconds from 1970-01-01T0:0:0Z as measured in UTC until the date/time.

Title: UserId
Description: End-User's user identification, the logical entity used to identify a user on a software, system, or websites.

Title: Name
Description: End-User's full name in displayable form including all name parts, possibly including titles and suffixes, ordered according to the End-User's locale and preferences.

Title: FirstName
Description: Given name(s) or first name(s) of the End-User. Note that in some cultures, people can have multiple given names; all can be present, with the names being separated by space characters.

Title: LastName
Description: Surname(s) or last name(s) of the End-User. Note that in some cultures, people can have multiple family names or no family name; all can be present, with the names being separated by space characters.

Title: MiddleName
Description: Middle name(s) of the End-User. Note that in some cultures, people can have multiple middle names; all can be present, with the names being separated by space characters. Also note that in some cultures, middle names are not used.

Title: EmailAddress
Description: End-User's preferred e-mail address. Its value MUST conform to the RFC 5322 [RFC5322] addr-spec syntax. This field is not guaranteed to be unique.

Title: NPI
Description: End-User's NPI number. Note that not all providers will have an NPI number.

Title: ProviderSpecialty
Description: The provider specialty. Note that not all providers will have a specialty.

Title: TimeZone
Description: String from [IANA](https://www.iana.org/time-zones) time zone database representing the End-User's time zone. For example, Europe/Paris or America/Los_Angeles.

Title: Locale
Description: End-User's locale, represented as a [BCP47 [RFC5646]](https://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47) language tag. This is typically an ISO 639-1 Alpha-2 [ISO6391] language code in lowercase and an ISO 3166-1 Alpha-2 [ISO31661] country code in uppercase, separated by a dash. For example, en-US or fr-CA. As a compatibility note, some implementations have used an underscore as the separator rather than a dash, for example, en_US; Relying Parties MAY choose to accept this locale syntax as well.

Title: PhoneNumber.Office
Description: End-User's preferred telephone number. E.164 [E.164] is RECOMMENDED as the format of this Claim, for example, +1 (425) 555-1212 or +56 (2) 687 2400. If the phone number contains an extension, it is RECOMMENDED that the extension be represented using the RFC 3966 [RFC3966] extension syntax, for example, +1 (604) 555-1234;ext=5678.

Title: Meta.Source
Description: Contains the information for the system initiating the message, including the source ID and name.

Title: Meta.Source.ID
Description: Identifies the system initiating the message. If you have multiple OAuth API keys per environment type, this value is required. If you have only one OAuth API key per environment type, or you're using legacy API keys, this value is optional.

Title: Meta.Source.Name
Description: Displays the name of the system initiating the message.

Title: Meta.Destinations[]
Notes: Required when sending data to Redox.
Description: Contains the information for the endpoint(s) receiving the request. A request must contain at least one destination, but asynchronous requests can have more than one destination. Synchronous requests like queries can only support one destination.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].ID
Description: Identifies the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Destinations[].Name
Description: Displays the name of the endpoint that the request is directed to.

Title: Meta.Logs[]
Description: Contains the log identifier(s) for the request.

Title: Meta.Logs[].ID
Description: Identifies the request log(s) that correspond to this request. You can use this value to locate the relevant log in the Redox dashboard for support and reference.

Title: Meta.Logs[].AttemptID
Description: Identifies the request log attempt value, which is useful when retries are possible.

Notes: Only use this field if a health system indicates you should. The code is specific to the health system's EHR and might not be unique across health systems. In general, the facility fields within the data models (e.g. OrderingFacility) are more reliable and informative.
Description: Code for the facility related to the message.
